    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-04-17T11:19:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-04-17T11:19:00-05:00" n="327"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <head>327. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Consulate General in Salisbury</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d327fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 745C.00/4-1762. Confidential. Drafted by Dunham on April 16 and
                        approved by <persName corresp="#p_DOH1">Deming</persName>. Repeated to
                        London and <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-04-17T11:19:00-05:00">April 17, 1962, 11:19 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>811. <gloss target="#t_UNIP1">UNIP</gloss> President Kenneth Kaunda discussed
                    Northern Rhodesian problems with Department officers April 13.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d327fn1">A memorandum of conversation is ibid.,
                        611.45C/4-2662.</note> He appealed for U.S. <pb facs="0544" n="516"
                        xml:id="pg_516"/> sympathy and political support, stressed that <persName
                        corresp="#p_WSR1">Welensky</persName>’s threat to use force to preserve
                    Federation should not be underestimated and declared that the present Federation
                    must be dissolved before useful discussions can be held concerning practical
                    relationships among the territories. Although outcome of Northern Rhodesian
                    elections in autumn uncertain, Kaunda confident that <gloss target="#t_UNIP1"
                        >UNIP</gloss> would emerge in better shape than any other party.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
